    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How much can I realistically save on groceries each month?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer"><p>Most families can save 30 to 50 percent on their grocery bill by combining meal planning, store brand purchases, coupon stacking, and strategic shopping. For a family spending $800 per month, that translates to $240 to $400 in monthly savings. Even implementing just two or three strategies, like meal planning and switching to store brands, can save $100 to $200 per month without significant lifestyle changes.</p></div>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Is buying in bulk always cheaper?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer"><p>Not always. Bulk buying saves money on shelf-stable items like rice, pasta, canned goods, and frozen foods where the unit price is genuinely lower and you will use the product before it expires. However, perishable items in large quantities can lead to food waste that negates any savings. Always compare the unit price on the shelf tag, and factor in whether you have the storage space and the consumption rate to justify a larger purchase.</p></div>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>Are store brand products lower quality than name brands?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer"><p>In most cases, no. Store brands are often manufactured in the same facilities as name brands and must meet the same FDA safety and quality standards. Consumer reports and blind taste tests consistently show that most people cannot distinguish between store brand and name brand products for staple items like canned vegetables, flour, sugar, pasta, and dairy products. Start by swapping a few items and decide for yourself.</p></div>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>What are the best apps for saving money on groceries?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer"><p>Popular grocery savings apps include Ibotta and Checkout 51 for cash-back rebates on specific products, Flipp for browsing digital circulars and matching coupons to sales, Basket for real-time price comparisons across stores in your area, and Flashfood for purchasing discounted items nearing their best-by date directly from local stores. Using two or three of these apps together can save $20 to $50 per month.</p></div>
    </details>

    <details class="faq-item">
      <summary>How do I start meal planning if I have never done it before?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer"><p>Start simple. Pick five to seven dinners for the week, writing down every ingredient you need for each meal. Check your pantry, refrigerator, and freezer for items you already have, then buy only what is missing. Build your meals around what is on sale that week at your grocery store. Over time, you will develop a rotation of affordable go-to recipes that simplify the process. Many beginners find it helpful to designate theme nights, like Taco Tuesday or Pasta Friday, to reduce decision fatigue.</p></div>
    </details>

